PAGE 3 — 1. Executive Summary
This project builds a Machine Learning model 
to predict cryptocurrency volatility using 
historical Bitcoin market data.

The model uses XGBoost Regressor trained on 
23 engineered features derived from OHLC prices,
trading volume, and market capitalization.

Final Model Performance:
- R² Score : 0.8183 (81% Accurate)
- RMSE     : 0.007201
- MAE      : 0.004658

The model is deployed as a Streamlit web 
application that predicts volatility in 
real-time based on user inputs.

PAGE 4 — 2. Problem Statement
Cryptocurrency markets are highly volatile. 
Understanding and forecasting this volatility 
is crucial for market participants.

Volatility refers to the degree of variation 
in the price of a cryptocurrency over time. 
High volatility can lead to significant risks 
for traders and investors.

Objective:
Build a machine learning model to predict 
cryptocurrency volatility levels based on:
- OHLC (Open, High, Low, Close) prices
- Trading Volume
- Market Capitalization

Goal:
Anticipate periods of heightened volatility,
enabling traders and financial institutions 
to manage risks and make informed decisions.

PAGE 5 — 3. Dataset Description
Source   : Cryptocurrency Historical Prices
Format   : CSV
Size     : 72,946 rows × 10 columns

Columns:
┌─────────────┬───────────┬────────────────────────┐
│ Column      │ Type      │ Description            │
├─────────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────┤
│ date        │ object    │ Trading date           │
│ crypto_name │ object    │ Cryptocurrency name    │
│ open        │ float64   │ Opening price          │
│ high        │ float64   │ Highest price of day   │
│ low         │ float64   │ Lowest price of day    │
│ close       │ float64   │ Closing price          │
│ volume      │ float64   │ Trading volume         │
│ marketCap   │ float64   │ Market capitalization  │
│ timestamp   │ object    │ Timestamp (removed)    │
└─────────────┴───────────┴────────────────────────┘

Cryptocurrencies : 50+
Missing Values   : 0
Focus            : Bitcoin (3248 rows)
Date Range       : 2013 to 2023

PAGE 6 — 4. Methodology
Step 1 — Data Collection
→ Loaded dataset.csv (72,946 rows)
→ Filtered Bitcoin data (3248 rows)
→ Saved bitcoin_clean.csv

Step 2 — Data Preprocessing
→ Removed unnecessary columns
→ Converted date to datetime format
→ Sorted data by date
→ Verified no missing values

Step 3 — Exploratory Data Analysis
→ Analyzed price trends
→ Plotted volatility over time
→ Created correlation heatmap
→ Analyzed Bollinger Bands
→ Analyzed RSI indicator
→ Analyzed trading volume

Step 4 — Feature Engineering
→ Created target variable (volatility_7d)
→ Created 23 features
→ Removed NaN rows
→ Final dataset: 3012 rows × 33 columns

Step 5 — Model Training
→ Trained Random Forest
→ Trained XGBoost
→ Compared results
→ Selected XGBoost as best model

Step 6 — Deployment
→ Built Streamlit web application
→ Real-time volatility prediction
→ Color coded risk output

PAGE 7 — 5. Feature Engineering Summary
Total Features Created : 23

Category          Features
─────────────────────────────────────────
Target Variable   volatility_7d

Price Features    MA_7, MA_14, MA_30
                  price_range
                  price_range_pct
                  close_open_pct

Technical         BB_width (Bollinger Bands)
Indicators        ATR_14 (Avg True Range)
                  RSI_14 (Relative Strength)

Volume Features   volume_MA7
                  volume_change
                  volume_spike
                  liquidity_ratio

Lag Features      volatility_lag1
                  volatility_lag3
                  volatility_lag7
                  return_lag1
                  return_lag3

Most Important Feature : volatility_lag1
Importance Score       : 0.78 (78%)

PAGE 8 — 6. Model Results
Two models were trained and compared:

┌───────────────┬──────────┬──────────┬────────┐
│ Model         │ RMSE     │ MAE      │ R²     │
├───────────────┼──────────┼──────────┼────────┤
│ Random Forest │ 0.007467 │ 0.005019 │ 0.8046 │
│ XGBoost       │ 0.007201 │ 0.004658 │ 0.8183 │
└───────────────┴──────────┴──────────┴────────┘

Winner : XGBoost ✅

Reason XGBoost Won:
- Lower RMSE (0.007201 vs 0.007467)
- Lower MAE  (0.004658 vs 0.005019)
- Higher R²  (0.8183 vs 0.8046)

Interpretation:
- R² = 0.8183 means model explains 
  81.83% of volatility variation
- RMSE = 0.007 means average error 
  is only 0.007 — very small!
- MAE = 0.004 means on average model 
  is off by only 0.004

PAGE 9 — 7. Key Insights
Insight 1 — Past Volatility Predicts Future
The most important feature was volatility_lag1
(previous day volatility) with 78% importance.
This shows volatility follows patterns.

Insight 2 — Price Range Matters
price_range_pct was 2nd most important.
Large daily price swings indicate 
upcoming volatile periods.

Insight 3 — Volume Spike = Volatility
When trading volume spikes unusually high,
it often precedes volatile price movements.

Insight 4 — Bollinger Bands Work
BB_width was among top features.
Wider bands = higher expected volatility.

Insight 5 — Bitcoin Has Volatile Phases
From EDA, Bitcoin showed extreme volatility
during 2017-2018 and 2020-2021 bull runs

PAGE 10 — 8. Deployment Summary
Tool          : Streamlit
File          : app.py
URL           : localhost:8501

Features:
- Professional dark theme UI
- Real-time volatility prediction
- Color coded risk levels
- Input summary display
- Model performance metrics shown

User Flow:
1. Open app at localhost:8501
2. Enter OHLC prices in sidebar
3. Enter Volume and Market Cap
4. Click Predict Volatility button
5. View prediction result

Risk Classification:
🔴 HIGH   → Volatility > 0.05
            Market is highly unstable
🟡 MEDIUM → Volatility 0.02 to 0.05
            Proceed with caution
🟢 LOW    → Volatility < 0.02
            Market is stable

